The key insight in solving this problem is to simplify the given congruence by reducing the coefficients modulo 20. This is done by dividing both sides of the congruence by the greatest common divisor (GCD) of the coefficients and the modulus. In this case, the GCD of 34, 6, and 20 is 2. By dividing both sides by 2, we can simplify the congruence and make it easier to solve.
We can simplify the congruence as follows (all of the following congruences are equivalent):

1. Divide both sides by 2 (the GCD of 34, 6, and 20):
$$\begin{align*}
34x+6&\equiv 2\pmod {20}\\
17x+3&\equiv 1\pmod {10}
\end{align*}$$

2. Subtract 3 from both sides:
$$\begin{align*}
17x&\equiv 8\pmod {10}
\end{align*}$$

3. Multiply both sides by 3 (the modular inverse of 17 modulo 10):
$$\begin{align*}
51x&\equiv 24\pmod {10}\\
x&\equiv 24\pmod {10}
\end{align*}$$

4. Since we are looking for the largest negative integer, we can subtract 10 from the right-hand side:
$$\begin{align*}
x&\equiv 14\pmod {10}\\
x&\equiv -6\pmod {10}
\end{align*}$$
Therefore, the largest negative integer $x$ that satisfies the congruence $34x+6\equiv 2\pmod {20}$ is $\boxed{-6}$.

